In Lucene query, the correct operator to use is `:` not `=`, so `fields.statusCode:xxx` which yields 24 results is the correct way to do it.

More info can be found on [Lucene query parser syntax](https://lucene.apache.org/core/8_2_0/queryparser/org/apache/lucene/queryparser/classic/package-summary.html#package.description) documentation.

Whatever you write inside the `Query` field in Grafana will end up in the `query_string` below:

    {
      &quot;size&quot;: 0,
      &quot;query&quot;: {
        &quot;bool&quot;: {
          &quot;filter&quot;: [
            {
              &quot;range&quot;: {
                &quot;@timestamp&quot;: {
                  &quot;gte&quot;: &quot;1571221609944&quot;,
                  &quot;lte&quot;: &quot;1571223409944&quot;,
                  &quot;format&quot;: &quot;epoch_millis&quot;
                }
              }
            },
            {
              &quot;query_string&quot;: {
                &quot;analyze_wildcard&quot;: true,
                &quot;query&quot;: &quot;fields.requestPath:\&quot;bla bla bla\&quot; AND XYZ AND method:POST&quot;
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      &quot;aggs&quot;: {
        ...
      }
    }

As you can see in the [`query_string` query syntax](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/query-dsl-query-string-query.html#query-string-syntax) (semantically equivalent to the one I shared above), the `:` is the character you need to use to separate field name and values.

